2.  Domestic Consulting Services Specialist/Team Leader (7 person-months) 

4.  The specialist will 
(i)  assess lessons learned in the pilot testing conducted under TA 3138-PRC 
and identify areas of improvement in the Guidelines; 
(ii)  collect  and  review  procedures  for  consulting  services  that  government 
agencies now use, including good and bad case studies;  
(iii)  update the Guidelines with a focus on ensuring they meet the PRC local 
requirements based on the review of (i) and (ii) above;  
(iv)  help  NDRC  organize,  and  provide  technical  inputs  into,  consultation 
workshops; 
(v)  draft the text of the Regulation based on the Guidelines; 
(vi)  present  the  draft  Regulation  to  the  Advisory  Committee  and  incorporate 
Committee comments before finalizing the Regulation;  
(vii)  help the domestic legal advisor finalize  the  draft  Regulation  for  NDRC’s 
approval (expected by the third quarter of 2005); 
(viii)  coordinate translation of the Regulation from Chinese into English; 
(ix)  help  NDRC  organize  new  release  conferences  for  dissemination  of  the 
Regulation; 
(x)  help the international consulting services specialist develop reference training 
materials to strengthen CNAEC’s training capacity in international standards 
and requirements for bidding for overseas projects, consulting profession 
code of ethics, and consultant-client relationships; 
(xi)  help  the  international  consulting  services  specialist  recommend  follow-up 
actions to further strengthen the regulatory framework for the PRC consulting 
industry;  
(xii)  help  the  international  consulting  services  specialist  recommend  ways  to 
strengthen  CNAEC’s  role  and  function  as  a  leading  sector  consulting 
association in the PRC; 
(xiii)  help NDRC develop the framework for a monitoring mechanism to enforce 
application of the Regulation and Guidelines;      
(xiv)  coordinate the daily work of consultants, and liaison among ADB, NDRC, and 
consultants and line ministries; and  
(xv)  prepare reports that ADB requires, in collaboration with other consultants.  

3.  Domestic Legal Advisor (3 person-months) 

5.  The advisor will 
(i)  review the revised Guidelines from a legal perspective; 
(ii)  review  legislation  relating  to  government  procurement  and  consulting 
services;   
(iii)  produce the draft Regulation, in legal language based on the text prepared by 
the domestic consulting services specialist and the content of the revised 
Guidelines;

      15
C.  Reports 
9.  Consultants will submit the following reports to ADB and the Government: 
(i)  an inception report within 2 weeks of the TA fieldwork that includes a detailed 
work plan, the time frame for finalization and approval of the Regulation, the 
methodology for drafting the Regulation, and the method for dissemination of 
the Regulation and Guidelines; 
(ii)  updated Guidelines within 1 month of submission of the inception report; 
(iii)      an interim report within 3 months after submission of the updated Guidelines 
that contains the draft Regulation and a training plan; 
(iv)  the  finalized  Regulation,  ready  for  NDRC  approval,  with  incorporated 
comments of ADB, NDRC, and the Advisory Committee; 
(v)  two sets of training manuals suitable for government agencies and consulting 
firms, upon NDRC approval of the Regulation; 
(vi)  a brief training evaluation report upon completion of each training program; 
(vii)  a draft final report at the end of month 15 for ADB and government review; 
and;  
(viii)  a final report 1 month after the final tripartite meeting. 

10.  Tripartite meetings will be held at the end of month 6 to discuss the draft Regulation, and 
at the end of month 17 to discuss the draft final report.
